{"parse":{"title":"bloom","pageid":55493,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Bloom|blööm|Blööm}}\n==English==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/bluːm/}}\n* {{audio|en|en-us-bloom.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{homophones|en|Bloom}}\n* {{rhymes|en|uːm|s=1}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{root|en|ine-pro|*bʰleh₃-}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|blome}}, from {{der|en|non|blóm}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*blōmô||flower}}. {{doublet|en}} of ''[[#Etymology_3|bloom]]'' (“spongy mass of metal”); see there for more.\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun|~}}\n\n# A [[blossom]]; the [[flower]] of a [[plant]]; an expanded [[bud]].\n#* {{RQ:Prescott Mexico\n|passage=the rich '''blooms''' and enamelled vegetation of the tropics}}\n# {{lb|en|collective}} Flowers.\n# {{lb|en|uncountable}} The opening of flowers in general; the state of blossoming or of having the flowers open.\n#: {{ux|en|The cherry trees are in '''bloom'''.}}\n#* {{RQ:Milton Paradise Lost|book=3|passage=sight of vernal '''bloom'''|year=1873}}\n#* {{RQ:Tennyson In Memoriam|II||O, not for thee the glow, the '''bloom''',<br>⁠Who changest not in any gale,<br>⁠Nor branding summer suns avail<br>To touch thy thousand years of gloom: […]}}\n# {{lb|en|figuratively}} A state or time of beauty, freshness, and [[vigor]]; an opening to higher [[perfection]], analogous to that of buds into blossoms.\n#: {{co|en|the '''bloom''' of youth}}\n#* {{RQ:Hawthorne Scarlet Letter|passage=every successive mother had transmitted to her child a fainter '''bloom''', a more delicate and briefer beauty.}}\n#* {{quote-song|en|lyricist=Kurt Cobain|title=In Bloom|album=Nevermind|artist=Nirvana|year=1992|passage=We can have some more / Nature is a whore / Bruises on the fruit / Tender age in '''bloom'''}}\n# Rosy colour; the flush or glow on a person's cheek.\n# The delicate, powdery [[coating]] upon certain growing or newly-gathered [[fruit]]s or leaves, as on grapes, plums, etc.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=2010|author=Donna Pliner Rodnitzky|title=Low-Carb Smoothies\n|passage=The '''bloom''' on blueberries is the dusty powder that protects them from the Sun; it does not rinse off.}}\n# Anything giving an appearance of attractive [[freshness]].\n#* {{RQ:Thackeray Vanity Fair|chapter=2|passage=a new, fresh, brilliant world, with all the '''bloom''' upon it}}\n# {{lb|en|countable|uncountable}} An [[algal bloom]].\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=2018|author=w:Tim Flannery|title=Europe: A Natural History|page=28|passage=Where upwellings or other sources of nutrients allow Ehux to abound, it can proliferate, as '''blooms''', to the point that the ocean turns milky.}}\n# The clouded appearance which [[varnish]] sometimes takes upon the surface of a picture.\n# A yellowish deposit or powdery coating which appears on well-tanned leather.<ref>{{R:Knight AMD}}</ref>\n# {{lb|en|mineralogy}} A bright-hued variety of some minerals.\n#: {{co|en|the rose-red cobalt '''bloom'''}}\n# {{lb|en|culinary}} A white area of [[cocoa butter]] that forms on the surface of [[chocolate]] when warmed and cooled.\n# A [[natural]] [[protective]] [[coating]] on an [[eggshell]].\n# {{lb|en|television}} An undesirable [[halo]] [[effect]] that may occur when a very [[bright]] region is displayed next to a very [[dark]] region of the screen.\n# {{lb|en|video games}} The increase in [[bullet]] spread over time as a gun's [[trigger]] is kept held.\n#* {{quote-web|en|url=https://critpoints.net/2018/02/21/bullet-bloom-an-fps-tragedy/|date=February 21, 2018|title=Bullet Bloom: An FPS Tragedy|work=CritPoints|text='''Bloom''' does add a skill element, burst firing the weapon instead of holding the trigger down, but it's questionable if adding a skill element like that is the actual intent of '''bloom''', because that’s a pretty lame and linear skill element to add, requiring people to tap the button instead of hold it down.}}\n# {{lb|en|Philippines|fandom slang|usually|in the plural}} A [[fan]] of Filipino [[girl group]] {{w|Bini (group)|BINI}}.\n# {{lb|en|collective}} A group of [[ladybug]]s.\n#* {{quote-journal|en|title=A gaggle, a confusion and a conspiracy - bizarre animal collective group names|magazine=w:BBC|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/newsround/48539466|date=2019-06-06|passage=Thousands of the little red and black insects took flight at the same time, and the '''bloom''' stretched for 10 miles before they landed.}}\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{sense|flower of a plant}} [[blossom]], [[flower]]\n* {{sense|opening of flowers}} [[blossom]], [[flower]]\n* {{sense|anything giving an appearance of attractive freshness}} [[flush]], [[glow]]\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col3|en|bloom is off the rose|violet bloom|bloomy|in bloom|algal bloom|bloom is off the peach|bloom tea|choking bloom|iron bloom|phytoplankton bloom|water bloom|zinc bloom|abloom|Bloomfield|bloomless|bloomly|bloomsome|checkerbloom|embloom|maybloom|nanobloom|sunbloom|superbloom|winterbloom}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-see|blossom}}\n\n{{trans-see|flower}}\n\n{{trans-top|the state of blossoming}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|цъфтеж|m}}, {{t+|bg|цъфтене|n}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|rozkvět|m}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kukinta}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|floraison|f}}, {{t|fr|en fleurs}}, {{t+|fr|efflorescence|f}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|fioritura|f}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|înflorire|f}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|цвет|m}}, {{t+|ru|расцве́т|m}}, {{t+|ru|цвете́ние|n}}\n* Sami:\n*: Northern Sami: {{t|se|lieđđun}}\n* Urdu: {{t|ur|کھلنا|tr=khilnā}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|state or time of beauty, freshness, and vigor}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|разцвет|m}}, {{t+|bg|свежест|f}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|fleur|f}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|ngarurutanga}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|цвет|m}}, {{t+|ru|расцве́т|m}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|delicate, powdery coating upon certain growing or newly-gathered fruits or leaves}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t|bg|пух|m}}\n* Catalan: {{t|ca|pruïna|f}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|rijp}}, {{t+|nl|waas|n}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|nukka}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|pruine|f}}, {{t+|fr|velours|m}}, {{t+|fr|duvet|m}}\n* German: {{t|de|Reifbelag|m}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|pruina|f}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|hanamā}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|brumă|f}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|pruina|f}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|anything giving an appearance of attractive freshness}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|the clouded appearance which varnish sometimes takes upon the surface of a picture}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|yellowish deposit or powdery coating which appears on well-tanned leather}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|mineralogy: a popular term for a bright-hued variety of some minerals}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kukka}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|fleur|f}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|white area of cocoa butter}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|harmaantuminen}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|voile|m}}, {{t+|fr|blanchiment|m}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|blanqueo|m}}, {{t|es|blanqueamiento|m}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{root|en|ine-pro|*bʰleh₃-}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|bloom||a blossom}}.\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To cause to [[blossom]]; to make [[flourish]].\n#* {{RQ:Hooker Laws|passage=Charitable affection '''bloomed''' them.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[bestow]] a bloom upon; to make blooming or [[radiant]].\n#* {{RQ:Milton Paradise Lost|book=IV|passage=The Tree of Life{{...}}'''blooming''' Ambrosial Fruit Of vegetable Gold.|year=1873}}\n#* {{RQ:Keats Lamia|poem=To Autumn|stanza=3|page=138|passage=Where are the songs of Spring? Ay, where are they? / Think not of them, thou hast thy music too,— / While barred clouds '''bloom''' the soft-dying day, / And touch the stubble-plains with rosy hue; [...]}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} Of a plant, to produce blooms; to open its blooms.\n#* {{RQ:Milton Paradise Lost|book=1|passage=A flower which once / In Paradise, fast by the tree of life, / Began to '''bloom'''.|year=1873}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|figuratively}} To spread; to slowly expand like a field of flowers that blossom in fits and spurts.\n#: {{ux|en|Shadows '''bloomed''' over the yard.}}\n#: {{ux|en|Anger '''bloomed''' up from his throat.}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|figuratively}} Of a person, business, etc, to [[flourish]]; to be in a state of healthful, growing youth and vigour; to show beauty and freshness.\n#* {{RQ:Heller Catch-22|The Soldier in White|171|Nurse Cramer had a cute nose and a radiant, '''blooming''' complexion dotted with fetching sprays of adorable freckles that Yossarian detested.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=May 13, 2017| author=Barney Ronay| title=Antonio Conte’s brilliance has turned Chelsea’s pop-up team into champions| work=the Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2017/may/13/antonio-conte-chelsea-champions-manager| passage=The attacking three have also been allowed to '''bloom'''. Liberated from deep defensive duties Eden Hazard has become more expressive, more obviously, flashily complete.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=a. 1788|author={{w|John_Logan_(minister)|John Logan}}|title=A Tale\n|passage=A better country '''blooms''' to view, / Beneath a brighter sky.}}\n# {{lb|en|cooking}} To bring out the flavor of a spice by cooking it in oil.\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|cooking|of chocolate}} To develop a layer of bloom (white, spotty areas of cocoa butter) due to repeated warming and cooling.\n# {{lb|en|cooking}} To let carbon dioxide to escape from coffee in order to improve the taste.\n# {{lb|en|cooking}} To hydrate ingredients (such as gelatin or yeast) before using them.\n#: {{syn|en|proof|q1=baking|rehydrate|q2=brewing}}\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{sense|produce blooms}} {{l|en|blossom}}, {{l|en|flower}}\n* {{sense|flourish}} {{l|en|blossom}}, {{l|en|flourish}}, {{l|en|thrive}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col3|en|bloomer|let a thousand flowers bloom|late bloomer|night-blooming jasmine|unbloomed|outbloom|overbloom|night-blooming cereus|rebloom}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|cause to bloom; make flourish}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t|bg|разцъфвам}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|[[saada]] [[kukkia|kukkimaan]]}}\n* Latin: {{t|la|vernō}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|зацвести́}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|florecer}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|blomma}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|make blooming or radiant}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-see|open its blooms|blossom}}\n\n{{trans-top|flourish}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t|bg|разцъфвам}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|flori}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kukkia}}\n* German: {{t+|de|blühen}}\n* Sami:\n*: Northern Sami: {{t|se|lieđđut}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|florecer}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t+|uk|цвісти́|impf}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|of chocolate}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|harmaantua}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|blome}}, from {{inh|en|ang|blōma|t=lump of metal}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*blōmô|t=flower}}. \n{{col-top|2|cog}}\nCognate with {{cog|frr|Bloom}}, {{m|frr|bluum}}, {{m|frr|blööm|t=flower}}, {{cog|stq|Bloume|t=flower}}, {{cog|fy,li|blom|t=flower}}, {{cog|bar|Bleame}}, {{m|bar|Bleaml}}, {{m|bar|Bleampl|t=flower}}, {{cog|nl|bloem}}, {{m|nl|blom|t=flower}}, {{cog|de|Blume|t=flower}}, {{cog|lb|Blumm|t=flower}}, {{cog|wym|błum|t=flower}}, {{cog|vls|blomme|t=flower}}, {{cog|yi|בלום|t=flower}}, {{cog|da|blomme|t=flower}}, {{cog|fo|blóma|t=flower}}, {{cog|is|blóm|t=flower}}, {{cog|nn|blom}}, {{m|nn|blome|t=flower}}, {{cog|sv|blomma|t=flower}}, {{cog|got|𐌱𐌻𐍉𐌼𐌰|t=lily}}, {{cog|xvn|*bluma|t=flower}}; also {{cog|br|bleuñv|t=flowers; flowering}}, {{cog|kw|blejan}}, {{m|kw|blejen}}, {{m|kw|bleujen}}, {{m|kw|bleujenn|t=blossom, flower}}, {{cog|ga|bláth|t=flower}}, {{cog|gv|blaa|t=flower; heyday}}, {{cog|gd|blàth|t=bloom, blossom, flower; consequence, effect; heyday}}, {{cog|cy|blodyn|t=flower}}, {{cog|la|flōs|t=blossom, flower}}, {{cog|el|φύλλο|t=leaf; blade; sheet; foil, plate}}, {{cog|hy|բող}}, {{m|hy|բոխի|t=a kind of bitter field-plant, probably horse fennel, Hippomarathrum or a kind of fennel or wild parsley}}, {{cog|xto|pält|t=leaf; blade}}, {{cog|txb|pilta|t=leaf; blade}}, {{cog|sa|फुल्ल|t=full-blown flower}}, {{m|sa|पुल्ल|t=flower}}. Related to {{m|en|blow}}, {{m|en|blade}}, {{m|en|blead}}; also related to [[flower]], [[foil]], and [[belladonna]].\n{{col-bottom}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# The [[spongy]] mass of [[metal]] formed in a [[furnace]] by the [[smelting]] process.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1957|author=H.R. Schubert|title=History of the British Iron and Steel Industry|page=26\n|passage=These metallic bodies gradually increasing in volume finally conglomerate into a larger mass, the '''bloom''', which is extracted from the furnace with tongs.}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|en|bloomery}}\n* {{l|en|blooming}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|the spongy mass of metal formed in a furnace by the smelting process}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t|bg|блума|f}}, {{t+|bg|брус|m}}\n* Danish: {{t|da|luppe|c}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|loupe}}\n* German: {{t|de|Luppe|f}}\n* Manx: {{t|gv|bloom|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|lupa|f}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|кри́ца|f}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|lupa|f}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n\n{{C|en|Fans (people)}}\n\n==Chinook Jargon==\n\n===Etymology===\nBorrowed from {{bor|chn|en|broom}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|chn|noun}}\n\n# [[broom]]\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|chn|mamook bloom}}"}}